'''''Anhuiphyton lineatum''''' is an extinct species of [[Neoproterozoic]] [[algae]], known from several fossils from the [[Lantian formation]] of [[China]],<ref name="Xunlai1999">{{Cite journal | last1 = Xunlai | first1 = Y. | last2 = Jun | first2 = L. I. | last3 = Ruiji | first3 = C. A. O. | doi = 10.1111/j.1502-3931.1999.tb00533.x | title = A diverse metaphyte assemblage from the Neoproterozoic black shales of South China | journal = Lethaia | volume = 32 | issue = 2 | pages = 143–155 | year = 1999 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref><ref name="Yuan2011">{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nature09810 | last1 = Yuan | first1 = X. | last2 = Chen | first2 = Z. | last3 = Xiao | first3 = S. | last4 = Zhou | first4 = C. | last5 = Hua | first5 = H. | title = An early Ediacaran assemblage of macroscopic and morphologically differentiated eukaryotes | journal = Nature | volume = 470 | issue = 7334 | pages = 390–3 | year = 2011 | pmid = 21331041|bibcode = 2011Natur.470..390Y }}</ref> first described in 1994.<ref name=Chen1994>{{cite journal|last=Chen|first=M.|author2=Xiao Z.|author3=Yuan X.|trans-title=A new assemblage of megafossils – Miaohe biota from Upper Sinian Doushantuo Formation in eastern Yangtze Gorges, China.|script-title=zh:晚震旦世的特种生物群落──庙河生物群新知|language=Chinese|journal=Acta Palaeontologica Sinica|year=1994|volume=33|issue=4|pages=391–403}}</ref> It lived probably more than 580 million years ago.<ref name="Yuan2011"/> The [[thallus|thalli]] were of spherical to elliptical shape, made of thousands of flexible [[septum|septated]] filaments.<ref name="Xunlai1999"/> The whole organism was a few centimeters in size (from 2.5 to 5&nbsp;cm at most).<ref name="Xunlai1999"/> Along with ''[[Flabellophyton]]'', it is one of the few septated algae found in the assemblage.

