{{Infobox Monarch||image=|caption=|succession=[[List of Trapezuntine emperors|Emperor]] of [[Empire of Trebizond|Trebizond]]<br><small>Claimant [[Byzantine Emperor]]</small>|reign=1235 – 1238|coronation=|predecessor=[[Andronikos I of Trebizond|Andronikos I]]|successor=[[Manuel I of Trebizond|Manuel I]]|spouse=|issue=|full name=|house=[[Komnenos dynasty|Komnenos]]|house-type=Dynasty|father=[[Alexios I of Trebizond|Alexios I Megas Komnenos]]|mother=possibly [[Theodora Axouchina]]|birth_date=|birth_place=|death_date=1238|death_place=|place of burial=|name=John I Axouchos|title=[[List of Byzantine Emperors|Emperor and Autocrat of the Romans]]<br /><small>''(Claimant)''</small>}}'''John I Axouchos'''<ref>[[William Miller (historian)|William Miller]], opines that "Axouchos" appears to have been a family name of the Komnenos, "for it had been borne by [[John Axouch|a Persian]], who had been Great Domestic at Constantinople". ''Trebizond: The Last Greek Empire of the Byzantine Era'', 1926 (Chicago: Argonaut, 1969), p. 24</ref> ({{lang-el|Ιωάννης Α΄ Αξούχος}}, ''Iōannēs I Axoukhos'') was Emperor of [[Empire of Trebizond|Trebizond]] from 1235 to 1238. One editor reads the text of the chronicle of [[Michael Panaretos]] as stating that John ruled six years; although William Miller follows [[Jakob Philipp Fallmerayer|Fallmerayer]] in assuming this was a mistake for three years,<ref>Miller, ''Trebizond'', p. 25 and note</ref> another possible solution is that John was co-ruler with his predecessor [[Andronikos I of Trebizond|Andronikos I Gidos]] for three years then ruled alone for three more.

He was the eldest son of [[Alexios I of Trebizond]] and a woman the primary sources do not identify; some writers have named her [[Theodora Axuchina]]. Miller suggests that he was perhaps a minor at the time of his father's death in 1222, for his father was succeeded by the throne passed to Alexis' son-in-law, Andronikos I Gidos.<ref>Miller, ''Trebizond'', p. 19</ref> During the [[Siege of Sinope]], one of the sources states that Alexios has "grown sons in Trebizond who are capable of governing", so it is clear John was born before 1214.<ref>[[Alexander Vasiliev (historian)|A. A. Vasiliev]], [https://www.jstor.org/stable/2846872 "The Foundation of the Empire of Trebizond (1204-1222)"], ''[[Speculum (journal)|Speculum]]'', '''11''' (1936), p. 27</ref>

Little is recorded of John's reign, except that John died while playing [[tzykanion]], a variant of polo fashionable among the Byzantine nobility, when he fell from his horse and was trampled to death.<ref>[[George Finlay]] (''The History of Greece and the Empire of Trebizond, (1204-1461)'', (Edinburgh: William Blackwood, 1851), p. 338 n. 1) discusses the possible locations of the hippodrome of Trebizond where John died.</ref> His heir apparent was one Ioannikios, who was confined to a monastery and John's second brother [[Manuel I of Trebizond|Manuel I]] ascended the throne. Since Fallmerayer, most historians have assume that Ioannikios was John Axouchos' son, but Panaretos' ''Chronicle'' does not state how Ioannikios was related to John Axouchos. Rustam Shukurov has argued that Ioannikios was the brother of both John and Manuel.<ref>Shukurov, [https://www.academia.edu/230484/Shukurov_R._The_enigma_of_David_Grand_Komnenos_Mesogeios._Vol._12._2001._P._125-136 "The enigma of David Grand Komnenos"], ''Mesogeios'', '''12''' (2001), pp. 131f (accessed 22 February 2014)</ref>

Older authorities credited John Axouchos with issuing the first silver coins, or [[aspron|aspers]] of the Empire of Trebizond,<ref>Warwick Wroth, ''Catalogue of the Coins of the Vandals, Ostrogoths and Lombards and of the Empires of Thessalonica, Nicaea and Trebizond in the British Museum'' (London: Trustees of the British Museum, 1911), pp. lxxviii, 232-235</ref> but more recent authorities believe these coins better fit with the aspers struck during [[John II of Trebizond|John II Megas Komnenos]] on numismatic grounds.<ref>A.A. Gordus and D.M. Metcalf, "Non-destructive Chemical Analysis of the Byzantine Silver Coinage of Trebizond", ''Archeion Pontou'', '''33''' (1975-1976), p. 29</ref>

