{{Infobox gridiron football person |birth_date={{Birth date|1941|8|18}} |birth_place=[[Waukesha, Wisconsin]] |death_date={{Death date and age|1964|5|28|1941|8|18}} |death_place =[[Missoula, Montana]] |Position=[[Defensive back]] |College=[[University of Montana|Montana]] |NFL=DIL369148 |playing_years1=1963 |playing_team1=[[Minnesota Vikings]] }} '''Terrance Gilbert Dillon''' (August 18, 1941 – May 28, 1964) was a [[defensive back]] in the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Dillon played with the [[Minnesota Vikings]] during the [[1963 NFL season]]. He had also been drafted in the 19th round of the [[1963 American Football League Draft]] by the [[Oakland Raiders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/D/DillTe20.htm|title=Terry Dillon|publisher=Pro-Football=Reference.com|accessdate=May 31, 2015}}</ref>
On May 28, 1964, Terry Dillon was working on a bridge construction project 25 miles west of Missoula when part of the temporary decking gave way and he fell 50 feet into the swift-running Clark Fork River. Witnesses said Dillon, a strong swimmer, started swimming for shore, fighting the current, but disappeared after traveling about 200 yards. His body was found on July 17th by a fisherman about 17 miles downstream from the bridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldestlivingprofootball.com/terrancegilbertdillon.htm|title=Terry Dillon|publisher=OldestLivingProFootballPlayers.com|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref>
In 1965, [[Minnesota Vikings]] [[linebacker]] [[Rip Hawkins]] received the first "Terry Dillon" award given by the Minnesota Vikings in honor of their late teammate. The award symbolizes Dillon's qualities of dedication, self-sacrifice and ability.
